### PHP Indexed Arrays

Indexed arrays use numeric indices, starting from 0 by default.

### Creating Indexed Arrays

```php
<?php
// Method 1
$cars = ["Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota"];

// Method 2
$cars[0] = "Volvo";
$cars[1] = "BMW";
$cars[2] = "Toyota";

// Method 3 - range()
$numbers = range(1, 5); // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
?>
```

### Accessing Elements

```php
<?php
$colors = ["Red", "Green", "Blue", "Yellow"];

echo $colors[0];   // Red
echo $colors[2];   // Blue

// Loop through
for ($i = 0; $i < count($colors); $i++) {
    echo $colors[$i] . " ";
}

// Or use foreach
foreach ($colors as $color) {
    echo "$color ";
}
?>
```

### Key Characteristics

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Default index | Starts at 0 |
| Auto-increment | New elements get next available index |
| Non-sequential | Can assign any index |
| Mixed indices | Can mix auto and manual indexing |

> **Key Point:** When you add elements with `[]`, PHP automatically uses the next available integer index (max integer key + 1).
